  <section class ="tutorial" role = "region" id="promises">
  <header role="header">
    <H1>Promises</H1> 	
    <div class="intro">
      We call our funding initiatives <span class="callout">Promises</span>.  A promise is a commitment you make to do something, in order to raise funds and awareness for a <span class="callout">Cause</span> you care about.
      </div> 
  </header>
      <ol class="summary">
        <li class="promisepart">The first part of a promise is that you promise to do something that is a personal challenge. We call this the <a class="callout" href="challenge">Challenge</a></li>
        <li class="promisepart">The second part of a promise is choosing a cause to support.  We call this part the <a href="Commitment" class="callout">Commitment</a></li>
        <li class="promisepart">The Third part of your promise the request for <a href="sponsors" class="callout">Sponsors</a> or <a href="co-promisers" class="callout">Co-Promisers</a>, we call this part the <a href="Promise" class="callout">Drive</a></li>
        <li class="promisepart">The fourth, and final part of your promise is getting proof that you've completed your commitment.  We call this part the <a href="proof" class="callout">Proof.</a>.  Once you've provided the proof, one of our specialists will review the proof against the original <span class="callout">Commitment</span></li>
      </ol>
      <div class = "expansion">
      	<p>Be, Cause is a crowd-funding site, but it's different than some of our friends out there in the crowd-funding space.  While most crowd-funding sites are helping people who make things, Be, Cause is about helping people trying to be something.  Specifically, we are about helping people who are trying to be a change for good in the world.</p>
        <p>Whether you are a charity looking for exposure, funding, and a community or a community member looking for a charity, we believe that we can get you connected.  That is how we are being the change we want to see.</p>  
        <p>As a member of Be Cause you have the opportunity to champion, co-champion, sponsor or share promises.  These promises are a commitment made by the champion, and supported by the co-champions and sponsors, to create a change in the world by funding a cause.</p>
        <p>When champions create promises they set a date in the future when the challenge will be met.  We suggest running the challenge for 45-60 days to give champions time to prepare for the challenge and to raise awareness and sponsors for the promise.</p>
      </div>
  </section>
  <section class="tuturial" id="people">
  	<header>
  		<h1>People</h1>
  		<div class="intro">The <span class="callout">Be, Cause</span> community contains several different types of people looking to make connections.</div>
  	</header>
    <dl>
    	<dt>Causes</dt>
    	<dd>Be, Cause requires that Causes be Non-Profit NGOs with the ability to prove their charitable status in the region they operate in.  While that's a fairly technical term what it really means is that any real charity could be a good candidate for funding.</dd>
    	<dt>Sponsors</dt>
    	<dd>For any given Promise a sponsor is a person who has pledged to donate on your behalf, if you  complete your challenge. You may be a sponsor on one promise, an a champion on another, which brings us to...</dd>
    	<dt>Champions</dt>
    	<dd>Of course every member of Be, Cause is a champion, but when we say <span class="callout">champion</span> we mean the champion behind a promise.  A promise may only have one champion, who is the person that created it and has made the commitment represented by that promise.  The champion must complete the challenge for the promise to get sponsored.  While a promise may only have champion, it may have many co-champions.</dd>
      <dt>Co-Champion</dt>
      <dd>A co-champion is a person who has commited to an existing promise.  By co-championing a promise you can bring your connections to that promise and hopefully earn that promise more awareness and more funding.</dd>
    </dl>
    <p>Every member of <span class="callout">Be, Cause</span> has the option of <a href="connections" class="callout">connecting</a> with other members of Be, Cause to create a network.  When someone is in your network they will recieve notifications obout all the promises you interact with.  These interactions are championing a new promise, co-championing an existing promise, sponsoring an existing promise or sharing a promise. These are the only interactions that get shared with your network, while Be, Cause does leverage the power of a network it is not a social networking tool.  We recommend using Be, Cause in conjunction with your social network or blogging platform of choice to maximize your impact.</p>
  </section>
  <section class="tutorial" id="accountability" role="region">
  	<header role="header">
  		<h1>Accountability</h1>
  		<div class="intro">Through this community you have the power to ask people to support causes your care about. With that ability comes a responsibility we take very seriously.</div>
  	</header>
  	<p>Accountability at Be, Cause is built on a reputation system.  This system is very similar to that used by the <a href="http://stackexchange.com/" class = "external">Stack Exchange Network</a></p>
  	<p>In  the interest of making it possible for anyone to champion a promise, there is no minimum reputation to sponsor or champion your first promise.</p>
  	<p>Whenever promises are created they are reviewed by our team, we will verify that the promise will help a real charity, that the Challenge is reasonable and can be audited.  Whenever a promise you championed passes this review you will gain <span class="pointscore">20 </span>reputation points. If you champion a promise and it fails this step, you will loose <span class="pointscore negative">25</span> reputation points.
    <p>Whenever promises are completed they are reviewed by our team.  We will verify that the challenge was completed, that the results were audited and that the audit supports the fact that the Challenge was completed.  Whenever one of your promises passes this stage you will receive <span class="pointscore">25</span> reputation points.  If a promise is completed but the challenge is not met, then you will loose <span class="pointscore negative">30</span> reputation points. </p>
    <p>As a sponsor, when a promise is completed and the challenge review has been met you will be required to honour your sponsorship commitment.  When you honour that commitment you will receive <span class="pointscore">10 </span>reputation points.  You also receive <span class="pointscore">5 </span>reputation points for sponsoring during the sponsorship drive for a promise. However, if you fail to meet your commitment as a sponsor you will loose <span class="pointscore negative">15</span> reputation points.</p>
    <p>As a co-champion you can receive <span class="pointscore">15</span> reputation points for joining a promise and <span class="pointscore">20</span> points for completing the challenge.  Leaving a promise before it's completed or failing to meet the challenge will cost <span class="pointscore negative">30</span> reputation points.</p> 
    <p>Sharing a promise with your network without getting involved will cause you to gain <span class="pointscore">1</span> reputation point.  You cannot loose reputation points through sharing a promise.</p>
    <p>Causes gain and loose reputation as well.  Causes gain 1 reputation point whenever anyone champions, co-champions, or sponsors a promise for that cause.  Causes loose reputation on a case by case basis, in response to observations brought to the network and after careful review.  Causes who suffer enough reputation loss may be blocked from the network for up to 30 days or banned altogether.</p>
    <p>It is possible to have a negative reputation.  Should you earn a negative reputation it is advisable to rebuild your reputation through sponsoring and sharing projects.  It is not possible to create a promise while you have a negative reputation.</p>
    <p>User accounts that reach <span class="pointscore negative">-50</span> reputation points will be blocked for 30 days, further reputation loss may lead to a banning.</p>
    <p>to create your second or subsequent promise you must have a reputation of at least <span class="pointscore">0</span> reputation points.
    <p>This reputation system protects everyone and ensures that everything is transparent.  It is always quick to see  who is being a positive force for change, and who might be trying to abuse the system.</p>
  </section>
  <section class="tutorial" id="alternatives" role = "region">
  	<header role ="header">
  		<h1>Alternatives</h1>
  		<div class="intro">The <span class="callout">Be, Cause</span> network is a great way to help existing charities.  However, there are other solutions for other projects.  We are very focused on doing this one thing very well, and recommend you investigate these other resources who may be able to offer different funding approaches.</div>
  	</header>
    <dl>
    	<dt>Kickstarter</dt> 
    	<dd><a href="http://www.kickstarter.com/" class="external">Kickstarter.com</a>, with a mandate focused around bringing creativity to life, the fine folks over at Kickstarter have created a huge awareness for crowdfunding for the arts. These site is a fantastic option for creators in the United States of America.</dd>
    	<dt>Indiegogo</dt>
    	<dd><a href="http://www.indiegogo.com/" class="external">Indiegogo.com</a> bills itself as "the world's funding platform" and while it doesn't have quite the same buzz around it as kickstarter, indiegogo is a fantastic resource for makers from all over the world.</dd>
    	<dt>Flattr</dt>
    	<dd><a href="http://www.flattr.com" class="external"></a> offers a way for creators to ask for microdonations. Be, Cause owes the people behind flattr an intellectual debt as they were pioneers in this field and if you are a maker, please strongly consider joining their network to ask the world to support your work.</dd>
    	<dt>Wordpress</dt>
    	<dd><a href="http://www.wordpress.com" class="external">Wordpress.com</a> continues to be a great way to raise awareness through blogging.  They offer a very stable platform, an active community and a great set of tools. We strongly suggest using wordpress in conjunction with <span class="callout">Be, Cause</span> in order to document your journey and why you are raising the funds for your cause.</dd>
    </dl>
  </section>
